' plan-58-A: the POSITIVE fixture, and the A/B boundary marker.
'
' This declaration satisfies every `check_buffer_slots` rule — OUT direction,
' exactly one BUFFER clause, named by RETURN, `List OF Byte` return, a SIZE
' expression over real slots. It therefore passes BOTH ctype gates cleanly (see
' the `-ast -ir` run below) and reaches the backend, where lowering the thunk
' fails with an explicit refusal naming CBuffer.
'
' That refusal is deliberate and load-bearing. plan-58-A ships vocabulary and
' rejection only; the marshaling is plan-58-B. Without the two guards in
' link_thunk.rs (§2.4), this file would lower CLEANLY: the staging loop would
' take the generic scalar-OUT arm, and the result marshal's `_` default would
' load a raw zeroed 8-byte stack word into RESULT_VALUE_REGISTER, which the
' caller then dereferences as a collection block. Garbage, no diagnostic — the
' exact failure mode this sub-plan exists to prevent.
'
' When plan-58-B lands, this fixture's golden changes from a lowering error to a
' successful build and run. That churn is the signal, not noise.
IMPORT io

LINK "demo" AS demo
  FUNC readBytes(n AS Integer) AS List OF Byte
    SYMBOL "demo_read"
    ABI (buf OUT CBuffer, n CInt64) AS status CInt32
    BUFFER buf SIZE n
    RETURN buf
  END FUNC
END LINK

FUNC main() AS Integer
  ' Calling it is what forces the thunk to be lowered.
  io::print(toString(len(demo::readBytes(16))))
  RETURN 0
END FUNC
